#: ../../../basic/install.rst:4
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:6
msgid ""
"In short, if you use one of the :ref:`supported systems<supported-systems>`, "
"run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:9
msgid ""
"pip install --upgrade pip\n"
"pip install \"psycopg[binary]\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:12
msgid ""
"and you should be :ref:`ready to start <module-usage>`. Read further for "
"alternative ways to install."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:16
msgid "Fun fact: there is no ``psycopg3`` package, only ``psycopg``!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:22
msgid "Supported systems"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:24
msgid ""
"The Psycopg version documented here has *official and tested* support for:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:26
msgid "Python: from version 3.10 to 3.14"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:28
msgid "Python 3.8 and 3.9 are supported before Psycopg 3.3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:29
msgid "Python 3.7 is supported before Psycopg 3.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:30
msgid "Python 3.6 is supported before Psycopg 3.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:32
msgid "PyPy: from version 3.10 to 3.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:34
msgid "PyPy 3.9 is supported before Psycopg 3.3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:35
msgid "**Note:** Only the pure Python installation is currently supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:37
msgid "PostgreSQL: from version 10 to 18"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:39
msgid ""
"**Note:** PostgreSQL `currently supported release`__ are actively tested in "
"the CI. Out-of-support releases are supported on a best-effort basis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:42
msgid "OS: Linux, macOS, Windows"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:44
msgid "Pip: 20.3 or newer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:48
msgid ""
"The tests to verify the supported systems run in `Github workflows`__: "
"anything that is not tested there is not officially supported. This includes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:53
msgid "Unofficial Python distributions such as Conda;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:54
msgid "Alternative PostgreSQL implementation;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:55
msgid "Other platforms such as BSD or Solaris."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:57
msgid ""
"If you use an unsupported system, things might work (because, for instance, "
"the database may use the same wire protocol as PostgreSQL) but we cannot "
"guarantee the correct working or a smooth ride."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:65
msgid "What to install?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:67
msgid ""
"There are a few different options to install Psycopg 3. This is a quick "
"summary of their differences; follow the links for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:73
msgid "Installation Option"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:74
msgid "Command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:75
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:76
msgid "Perfor­mance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:77
msgid "Needs Local libpq?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:78
msgid "Needs Build Tools?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:80
msgid ":ref:`binary-installation` (recommended for most users)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:81
msgid "``pip install psycopg[binary]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:82
msgid "Precompiled C extensions, packaged with client libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:83 ../../../basic/install.rst:91
msgid "🐇 Fast"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:84 ../../../basic/install.rst:85
#: ../../../basic/install.rst:100
msgid "❌ No"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:87
msgid ":ref:`local-installation`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:88
msgid "``pip install psycopg[c]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:89
msgid ""
"Builds C extensions from source. Requires build tools and client libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:92 ../../../basic/install.rst:93
#: ../../../basic/install.rst:99
msgid "✅ Yes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:95
msgid ":ref:`pure-python-installation`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:96
msgid "``pip install psycopg``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:97
msgid "Pure Python implementation only. Requires client libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:98
msgid "🐢 Slow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:106
msgid "Binary installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:108
msgid ""
"The quickest way to start developing with Psycopg 3 is to install the binary "
"packages by running::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:111
msgid "pip install \"psycopg[binary]\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:113
msgid ""
"This will install a self-contained package with all the libraries needed. If "
"you are coming from Psycopg 2, this is the equivalent of installing the "
"``psycopg2-binary`` package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:119
msgid ""
"Did Psycopg 3 install ok? Great! You can now move on to the :ref:`basic "
"module usage <module-usage>` to learn how it works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:122
msgid ""
"Keep on reading if the above method didn't work and you need a different way "
"to install Psycopg 3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:125
msgid ""
"For further information about the differences between the packages see :ref:"
"`pq-impl`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:128
msgid ""
"If your platform is not supported, or if the libpq packaged is not suitable, "
"you should proceed to a :ref:`local installation <local-installation>` or a :"
"ref:`pure Python installation <pure-python-installation>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:134
msgid ""
"Binary packages are produced on a best-effort basis; the supported platforms "
"depend on the CI runners available to build the packages. This means that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:138
msgid ""
"binary packages for a new version of Python are made available once the "
"runners used for the build support it. You can check the `psycopg-binary "
"PyPI files`__ to verify whether your platform is supported;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:143
msgid ""
"the libpq version included in the binary packages depends on the version "
"available on the runners. You can use the `psycopg.pq.version()` function "
"and `~psycopg.pq.__build_version__` constant to infer the features available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:153
msgid ""
"Starting from Psycopg 3.1.20, ARM64 macOS binary packages (i.e. for Apple M1 "
"machines) are no more available for macOS versions before 14.0. Please "
"upgrade your OS to at least 14.0 or use a :ref:`local <local-installation>` "
"or a :ref:`Python <pure-python-installation>` installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:159
msgid "The binary installation is not supported by PyPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:166
msgid "Local installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:168
msgid ""
"A \"Local installation\" results in a performing and maintainable library. "
"The library will include the speed-up C module and will be linked to the "
"system libraries (``libpq``, ``libssl``...) so that system upgrade of "
"libraries will upgrade the libraries used by Psycopg 3 too. This is the "
"preferred way to install Psycopg for a production site."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:174
msgid "In order to perform a local installation you need some prerequisites:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:176
msgid "a C compiler,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:177
msgid "Python development headers (e.g. the ``python3-dev`` package)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:178
msgid "PostgreSQL client development headers (e.g. the ``libpq-dev`` package)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:179
msgid "The :program:`pg_config` program available in the :envvar:`PATH`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:181
msgid ""
"You **must be able** to troubleshoot an extension build, for instance you "
"must be able to read your compiler's error message. If you are not, please "
"don't try this and use the :ref:`binary-installation` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:185
msgid "If your build prerequisites are in place you can run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:187
msgid "pip install \"psycopg[c]\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:189
msgid ""
"This will install a self-contained package with all the libraries needed. If "
"you are coming from Psycopg 2, this is the equivalent of installing the "
"``psycopg2`` package, both in terms of build requirements and system "
"dependencies at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:196
msgid "The local installation is not supported by PyPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:202
msgid "Pure Python installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:204
msgid "If you simply install::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:206
msgid "pip install psycopg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:208
msgid ""
"without ``[c]`` or ``[binary]`` extras you will obtain a pure Python "
"implementation. This is particularly handy for debugging and hacking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:213
msgid ""
"The pure Python installation is much slower than the :ref:`binary-"
"installation` or :ref:`local-installation`. It is likely sufficient for "
"local developments or small tasks but, for production loads, you might want "
"to install one of the speed-up extensions too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:218
msgid ""
"In order to use the pure Python installation you will need the ``libpq`` "
"PostgreSQL client library installed on your client (which will be imported "
"dynamically via `ctypes`); for example on Debian systems you will probably "
"need::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:223
msgid "sudo apt install libpq5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:225
msgid ""
"If you are not able to fulfill this requirement please use a :ref:`binary-"
"installation`, which packages its own copy of the ``libpq``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:230
msgid ""
"The ``libpq`` is the client library also used by :program:`psql`, the "
"PostgreSQL command line client, to connect to the database.  On most "
"systems, installing :program:`psql` will install the ``libpq`` too as a "
"dependency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:239
msgid "Installing the connection pool"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:241
msgid ""
"The :ref:`Psycopg connection pools <connection-pools>` are distributed in a "
"separate package from the `!psycopg` package itself, in order to allow a "
"different release cycle."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:245
msgid ""
"In order to use the pool you must install the ``pool`` extra, using ``pip "
"install \"psycopg[pool]\"``, or install the `psycopg_pool` package "
"separately, which would allow to specify the release to install more "
"precisely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:253
msgid "Handling dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:255
msgid ""
"If you need to specify your project dependencies (for instance in a "
"``requirements.txt`` file, ``setup.py``, ``pyproject.toml`` dependencies...) "
"you should probably specify one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:259
msgid ""
"If your project is a library, add a dependency on ``psycopg``. This will "
"make sure that your library will have the ``psycopg`` package with the right "
"interface and leaves the possibility of choosing a specific implementation "
"to the end user of your library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:264
msgid ""
"If your project is a final application (e.g. a service running on a server) "
"you can require a specific implementation, for instance ``psycopg[c]``, "
"after you have made sure that the prerequisites are met (e.g. the depending "
"libraries and tools are installed in the host machine)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:269
msgid ""
"In both cases you can specify which version of Psycopg to use using "
"`requirement specifiers`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/install.rst:274
msgid ""
"If you want to make sure that a specific implementation is used you can "
"specify the :envvar:`PSYCOPG_IMPL` environment variable: importing the "
"library will fail if the implementation specified is not available. See :ref:"
"`pq-impl`."
msgstr ""
